By the fundamental theorem of calculus, we know that there exists a
function g(x) such that

\begin{align*}F(x) = \int_{0}^{x^{2}}f(t)\,dt = g(x^{2}) - g(0)\end{align*}

where g(x) is the anti-derivative of the function f(x) (i.e: g'(x) =
f(x)). Taking the derivative of F(x) gives

\begin{align*}F'(x) = \frac{d}{dx}\left(g(x^{2}) - g(0) \right) = g'(x^2)\cdot 2x\end{align*}

by the chain rule. Using the anti-derivative property of g,

\begin{align*}F'(x) = f(x^2)\cdot 2x.\end{align*}

Plugging in x = 2 and using the fact that f(4) = 1 gives us our answer

\begin{align*}F'(2) = f(4)\cdot 4 = 4\end{align*}
